<div class="tab-content active" id="notes-2-7">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>This section is pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Reasons for Government Intervention</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Earn government revenue (indirect taxes)</li>
      <li>Support firms (subsidies)</li>
      <li>Support households on low incomes (price ceilings, transfers)</li>
      <li>Influence the level of production or consumption</li>
      <li>Correct market failure (externalities, public goods)</li>
      <li>Promote equity in distribution</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Price Controls</h2>

    <h3>Price Ceiling (Maximum Price)</h3>
    <p>A <strong>price ceiling</strong> is set <em>below</em> the equilibrium price. It is intended to keep prices affordable for consumers.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Results in <strong>excess demand</strong> (shortage): Qd > Qs at the ceiling price</li>
      <li>Examples: rent controls, maximum food prices in wartime</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Consequences: shortages, black markets, reduced quality, non-price rationing (queues, rationing systems), reduced incentive for producers to supply.</p>

    <h3>Price Floor (Minimum Price)</h3>
    <p>A <strong>price floor</strong> is set <em>above</em> the equilibrium price. It is intended to guarantee producers a minimum income or prevent prices from falling too low.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Results in <strong>excess supply</strong> (surplus): Qs > Qd at the floor price</li>
      <li>Examples: minimum wage, EU Common Agricultural Policy (CAP)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Consequences: surpluses (government may need to buy up excess), higher prices for consumers, welfare loss.</p>

    <div class="callout hl-only">
      <div class="callout-title">HL only — Calculations</div>
      <p>At a price ceiling P<sub>c</sub>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Read off Qs and Qd from the diagram at P<sub>c</sub></li>
        <li>Shortage = Qd − Qs</li>
        <li>Consumer expenditure = P<sub>c</sub> × Qs (only Qs units are available)</li>
        <li>Producer revenue = P<sub>c</sub> × Qs</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top:0.5rem;">At a price floor P<sub>f</sub>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Surplus = Qs − Qd</li>
        <li>Consumer expenditure = P<sub>f</sub> × Qd</li>
        <li>Producer revenue = P<sub>f</sub> × Qs</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Indirect Taxes</h2>
    <p>An <strong>indirect tax</strong> is a tax on goods and services (not on income). It is paid by the producer to the government, but the burden is shared between producers and consumers depending on PED and PES.</p>

    <h3>Effect on the market</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The tax increases the cost of production → supply curve shifts <strong>left</strong> by the amount of the tax</li>
      <li>A new equilibrium is reached with a <strong>higher price</strong> and <strong>lower quantity</strong></li>
      <li>The <strong>tax burden</strong> is shared: consumers pay a higher price; producers receive a lower net price</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Tax incidence and elasticity</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>If demand is <strong>inelastic</strong> relative to supply, consumers bear a <strong>larger share</strong> of the tax</li>
      <li>If demand is <strong>elastic</strong> relative to supply, producers bear a <strong>larger share</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout hl-only">
      <div class="callout-title">HL only — Calculating tax incidence</div>
      <p>From the diagram, with a tax of $t per unit:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>New consumer price = P<sub>c</sub> (price consumers pay after tax)</li>
        <li>New producer price = P<sub>p</sub> = P<sub>c</sub> − t (price producers receive)</li>
        <li>Consumer burden = P<sub>c</sub> − P* (rise in price paid)</li>
        <li>Producer burden = P* − P<sub>p</sub> (fall in price received)</li>
        <li>Government tax revenue = t × Q<sub>new</sub></li>
        <li>Welfare loss = ½ × t × (Q* − Q<sub>new</sub>)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Subsidies</h2>
    <p>A <strong>subsidy</strong> is a payment by the government to producers to lower their costs of production. It shifts the supply curve <strong>right</strong>.</p>
    <p>Effects:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Lower equilibrium price for consumers</li>
      <li>Higher quantity produced and sold</li>
      <li>Producers receive a higher effective price (market price + subsidy)</li>
      <li>Government expenditure = subsidy per unit × quantity</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Subsidies are used to: support domestic industries, encourage consumption of merit goods, keep essential goods affordable, support low-income households.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Price ceiling below equilibrium → shortage</li>
      <li>Price floor above equilibrium → surplus</li>
      <li>Indirect tax → supply shifts left → higher P, lower Q, shared tax burden</li>
      <li>Subsidy → supply shifts right → lower P, higher Q</li>
      <li>Inelastic demand → consumers bear more of tax burden</li>
      <li>Elastic demand → producers bear more of tax burden</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="worked-2-7">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Worked examples are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Worked Example — Indirect Tax <span class="hl-badge">HL</span></h2>
  <p>The market for cigarettes has equilibrium at P* = $10, Q* = 1,000. The government imposes a tax of $4 per pack. The new equilibrium is: consumers pay P<sub>c</sub> = $13, producers receive P<sub>p</sub> = $9, Q<sub>new</sub> = 800.</p>

  <h3>Consumer burden per unit</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    P<sub>c</sub> − P* = $13 − $10 = <strong>$3 per pack</strong>
  </div>

  <h3>Producer burden per unit</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    P* − P<sub>p</sub> = $10 − $9 = <strong>$1 per pack</strong><br>
    Check: $3 + $1 = $4 = total tax ✓<br>
    Consumers bear 75% of the tax burden; producers bear 25% — demand is inelastic relative to supply.
  </div>

  <h3>Government tax revenue</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    Tax revenue = $4 × 800 = <strong>$3,200</strong>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-7">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Using a diagram, explain the effects of a price ceiling on a housing market. Identify the consequences for consumers and producers.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          A price ceiling on rent is set below equilibrium. At the ceiling price, Qd > Qs — more people want housing than is available. Consequences: <strong>consumers</strong> who obtain housing pay lower rent (benefit) but many consumers cannot find housing due to the shortage. <strong>Producers (landlords)</strong> receive lower rent and earn less revenue; some may exit the market or reduce maintenance, lowering the quality of housing. Non-price rationing (waiting lists, personal connections) replaces the price mechanism.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Explain how the burden of an indirect tax is distributed between consumers and producers when demand is price inelastic.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          When demand is price inelastic, consumers are not very responsive to price changes. When a tax raises the price, quantity demanded falls only slightly. The price consumers pay rises significantly (close to the full tax amount), while the price producers receive falls only a little. Therefore, the majority of the tax burden falls on consumers. The more inelastic the demand relative to supply, the greater the consumer share of the tax burden.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. <span class="hl-badge">HL</span> A market has equilibrium at P* = $20, Q* = 500. A subsidy of $5 per unit shifts the supply right. The new equilibrium is P<sub>consumer</sub> = $17, Q<sub>new</sub> = 560. Calculate (a) the price producers receive, (b) total government expenditure on the subsidy, and (c) the benefit to consumers and producers per unit.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          (a) Price producers receive = $17 + $5 = <strong>$22</strong><br>
          (b) Government expenditure = $5 × 560 = <strong>$2,800</strong><br>
          (c) Consumer benefit per unit = P* − P<sub>consumer</sub> = $20 − $17 = <strong>$3</strong><br>
          Producer benefit per unit = P<sub>producers receive</sub> − P* = $22 − $20 = <strong>$2</strong><br>
          Total = $3 + $2 = $5 = subsidy ✓
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

